          "body": "Joab's killing of Abner (3:27) is one of the most carefully narrated murders in the Old Testament. The narrator builds to it with four uses of 'sent him away in peace' (3:21-24), ensuring the reader feels the irony of each repetition before the violence arrives. Joab's motive is disclosed without ambiguity: 'because he had put their brother Asahel to death' (3:30; cf. 2:23). This is blood vengeance — an ancient institution with genuine moral weight in the Old Testament world (Gen 9:6; Num 35:19) — but enacted in a way that violates multiple boundaries: it is done secretly (3:26-27), in a city of refuge (Hebron, Josh 20:7), under the guise of diplomatic speech, by David's own general. The result is that Joab defiles the very peace David has established, imperils David's credibility with the northern tribes, and sheds innocent blood at the city gate. David's curse in 3:29 is not an outburst; it is a formal act of justice by the king who cannot — yet — exercise judicial power over Zeruiah's sons (3:39)."
