          "title": "The weak-yet-anointed king — restraint as faith",
          "body": "The chapter closes on a note of unusual royal vulnerability: 'I am weak today, though anointed king; and these men the sons of Zeruiah are too difficult for me' (3:39). David's self-assessment is not a lament of despair; it is an act of theological realism. He is anointed — the divine credential is secure — and yet he cannot yet enforce justice on the most violent men in his own court. His response is neither vengeance (which would endanger his coalition) nor silence (which would suggest complicity). He curses Joab formally (3:29), grieves publicly, and then commits the judgment to the LORD: 'May the LORD repay the evildoer according to his evil' (3:39). This is faith operating under institutional weakness — the same posture the Psalms will articulate repeatedly for David. The kingdom comes, but not all at once. The anointed king waits, restrained by circumstance, trusting that the one who swore the oath will also execute the judgment."
