        "excerpt": "As the LORD has sworn to David, I do not accomplish this for him, to transfer the kingdom from the house of Saul and to establish the throne of David over Israel and over Judah, from Dan even to Beersheba.",
        "body": "The quarrel over Rizpah (3:7-8) is the chapter's trigger, but it is not the chapter's meaning. Ish-bosheth accuses Abner of sleeping with his father's concubine — in the ancient Near East, appropriating a king's concubine was a claim to succession (cf. 2 Sam 16:21-22; 1 Kings 2:22). Whether Ish-bosheth's accusation is accurate matters less than its effect: it exposes the fragility of the house of Saul. A weak king accuses his only military pillar of high treason and cannot follow through. Abner's furious response (3:8-10) is self-righteous, but it contains a theological confession that the narrator takes seriously: the LORD has sworn to David, the kingdom will transfer, and Abner intends to make it happen.\n\nAbner's double citation of the divine oracle (3:9-10, then 3:18 to the elders) is the chapter's most striking feature. An enemy of David — a man defending his own wounded pride — twice articulates the Davidic covenant with precision. This is the biblical narrator's technique of placing theological truth on the lips of unexpected witnesses. It functions like Caiaphas's unwitting prophecy in John 11:49-52: the speaker does not intend to serve God's purpose, but the words themselves do. Abner knows the oracle. Israel's elders know it (3:17, 'in times past you were seeking for David'). Even Benjamin, Saul's own tribe, hears it (3:19). The consent that Abner gathers is not manufactured by political pressure; it is the crystallization of a recognition that has existed for years.\n\nDavid's one condition before accepting Abner's offer is the return of Michal (3:13-14). Commentators debate whether this is purely political (reclaiming Saul's daughter to legitimize his rule over the north) or personally motivated (restoring his first wife, taken from him under Saul, 1 Sam 18:20-27; 25:44). The text does not adjudicate the question — and this ambiguity is characteristic of the David narratives. David is fully human, with personal desires and political calculations operating simultaneously. What the narrator does show us is that Ish-bosheth complies immediately (3:15), confirming that Abner has already stripped him of real authority. The king who cannot protect his generals cannot protect his household.\n\nThe feast David makes for Abner and his twenty men (3:20) is a covenant-ratification ceremony in miniature — hospitality was the ancient Near Eastern seal of a new alliance. David sends Abner away in peace (shalom, 3:21), the narrator repeating the word four times in the next four verses as if building a foundation that Joab will demolish. The movement from peace to murder is the chapter's central tragedy.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Karat berit* — 'cut a covenant' — derives from the covenant ritual of cutting animals (Gen 15:10-17). The idiom is diplomatic-legal: Abner's proposed covenant (3:12) and David's agreement (3:13) are political treaties with binding force. *Mamlakhah* (kingdom, 3:10) is the dynastic realm — not merely a geographic territory but the institutional structure of royal rule."
