        "title": "Joab's murder — private vengeance against covenantal peace",
        "range": "3:22-30",
        "excerpt": "So when Abner returned to Hebron, Joab took him aside into the middle of the gate to speak with him privately, and there he struck him in the belly so that he died on account of the blood of Asahel his brother.",
        "body": "Joab's return from a raid (3:22) is structurally juxtaposed to Abner's departure in peace. The two worlds — David's diplomacy and Joab's warfare — collide at the threshold. Joab's accusation that Abner came to deceive David and spy on him (3:25) is plausible on its face — Abner was a military commander operating behind enemy lines. But the narrator has already shown us Abner's genuine political realignment with the elders and Benjamin, and the feast with David at Hebron was public knowledge. Joab's suspicion may be real, but the narrator frames it as pretext, not evidence: the actual motive is stated plainly in 3:30.\n\nThe murder itself is narrated with cold economy. Joab takes Abner aside 'to speak with him privately' — the pretense of diplomatic conversation masking the act of violence. The gate of Hebron was the city's public legal space, the location of judicial proceedings and official transactions. To kill a man at the gate is to commit homicide in the most public and legally significant space the city possessed. And Hebron was a designated city of refuge (Joshua 20:7; 21:13), where those who had killed without premeditation could flee from the avenger of blood and receive protection until trial. By murdering Abner at Hebron's gate, Joab violates every protection the city was designed to provide.\n\nThe verb used for Joab's act in 3:27 is *nakah* — 'to strike' — the same verb used for Joab's blow that felled Abner in the stomach (*chomesh*, the fifth rib or abdomen). It is the same location where Abner had struck Asahel at Gibeon (2:23). The verbal and anatomical echo is deliberate: Joab is acting as if he is executing blood vengeance in the formal sense. But the narrator will not allow that framing to stand. Numbers 35:16-21 distinguishes legitimate blood vengeance from premeditated murder; Joab has used the pretense of private conversation and acted without legal process in a city of refuge. The narrator's word in 3:30 is *harag* — 'murdered' — not the vocabulary of legitimate vengeance.\n\nDavid's ignorance (3:26) is the narrator's exculpation. It is stated parenthetically, as a legal finding. The king did not send for Abner; Joab sent his own messengers. The blood is on Joab's hands, not David's — a distinction that will matter to all Israel (3:37) and to the LORD (3:28).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chomesh* (belly/fifth rib, 3:27) echoes 2:23 exactly — the narrator connects the murders anatomically. *Harag* (3:30, 'murdered') is stronger than *nakah* ('strike') and carries the connotation of unjust killing. The distinction between *nakah* (the act) and *harag* (the narrator's verdict) is theologically significant."
